Name: ADAMS
notes: county website has some PDF maps under Public Works, and links to federal or state   sources

Name: Othello
notes: city website lists city council minutes through 2016, and has PDFs of various documents

Name: ASOTIN
notes: county website notes that Public Works can help residents with GIS data

Name: Clarkston
notes: city website has annual financial report, interlocal agreements, weekly records of building permits

Name: BENTON
notes: "OnlineMapping&Downloads" page on the county's webpages provide Esri-generated maps, along with shapefiles, KML, PDFs and metadata on various districts; search of home page for "data" takes the user to results that aren't intuitive (the right one is the third result, "GIS")

Name: Kennewick
notes: 62 datasets mostly about stormwater, public utilities

Name: CHELAN
notes: NA

Name: Wenatchee
notes: City maintains a Maps page with both interactive web-based maps and PDFs (http://www.wenatcheewa.gov/government/public-works/city-maps), as well as an ArcGIS site (https://maps.wenatcheewa.gov/arcgis/home/gallery.html) which appears to house just interactive maps or applications

Name: CLALLAM
notes: provides downloadable GIS data for zoning, water body maps etc.; also provides some interactive online maps

Name: Port Angeles
notes: city website actually has at least three open data portals (Socrata: open budget, open books, open payroll) as well as an arcGIS.com site (but this appears to include only web-interactive maps)

Name: CLARK
notes: Clark Co's website has a "Data and Reports" page with very pretty PDFs on topics incl. animal control, building inspections, code enforcement, land use, fire safety. Clark offers interactive Esri maps on its site, but the datasets aren't downloadable. Clark also has a GIS site (https://gis.clark.wa.gov/gishome/) which offers premium subscriptions (??) to GIS for more user-friendly tools and access to county records (https://gis.clark.wa.gov/gishome/mapstore/#/webPremium); https://www.clark.wa.gov/community-development/data-and-reports

Name: Vancouver
notes: Vancouver's website allows visitors to search a database of bids/RFPs (ProcureWare), but I don't see a way to download dataset; Vancouver's city site points users to  the CREDC (business development) website, which features statistics (but not datasets)

Name: COLUMBIA
notes: Posts some property sales data on city website, in PDF

Name: Dayton
notes: City website includes some PDF maps, and certain commission minutes thru 2017

Name: COWLITZ
notes: has GIS data & parcel data available in one (1) zip File; can't inspect the contents, so will record GIS maps only

Name: Longview
notes: has Esri online GIS interface at http://www.mylongview.com/index.aspx?page=700

Name: DOUGLAS
notes: includes parcel sales data, based on file titles

Name: East Wenatchee
notes: City maintains a "city documents" page housing various PDFs in a Windows folders format. Page talks a lot about sunshine, accountability and transparency. http://www.east-wenatchee.com/government/city-documents

Name: FERRY
notes: three Shapefiles on election precincts, roads, parcels

Name: Republic
notes: NA

Name: FRANKLIN
notes: County website includes some residential sales data, in PDF

Name: Pasco
notes: city does have PDFs of maps and other info, including a guide to social media pages! (http://www.pasco-wa.gov/239/PublicationsSocial-Media)

Name: GARFIELD
notes: website includes an interactive parcel search, and a few PDF maps

Name: Pomeroy
notes: city has various minutes and other documents housed on website

Name: GRANT
notes: County also has ArcGIS gallery (http://grantcountywa.maps.arcgis.com/home/gallery.html?view=grid&sortOrder=asc&sortField=title#c=organization&o=title) but this appears to be web-based interactive maps

Name: Moses Lake
notes: City has ArcGIS maps gallery (https://cityofml.maps.arcgis.com/home/index.html), which appears to be all web-based interactive maps; not obvious that you can download underlying dataset

Name: GRAYS HARBOR
notes: appears to be mainly maps, but "About Grays Harbor" webpage with basic statistics provides a link to the county's Council of Governments site, which includes more statistics and links to open data sets (http://www.co.grays-harbor.wa.us/visitors/about_grays_harbor/index.php)

Name: Aberdeen
notes: NA

Name: ISLAND
notes: county website also has more DIY "legacy" data download page (https://www.islandcountywa.gov/maps/Pages/Data.aspx)

Name: Oak Harbor
notes: NA

Name: JEFFERSON
notes: county website has an "Open Government Training" webpage with links to GIS, online mapping and Laserfiche (https://www.co.jefferson.wa.us/289/Open-Government-Training)

Name: Port Townsend
notes: Has City Council docs posted via Laserfiche (http://weblink.cityofpt.us/weblink/Browse.aspx?dbid=0) and one interactive map on ArcGIS (https://www.arcgis.com/home/webmap/viewer.html?webmap=0a7a496f18c44e27b2a58d51036d86a2)

Name: KING
notes: NA

Name: Seattle
notes: NA

Name: KITSAP
notes: NA

Name: Bremerton
notes: Bremerton PD makes xls stats available on arrests, incidents, citations; the page is not easy to find from the official website -- not obvious even with searches of "data,""statistics," or "crime." City also has a GIS page but the maps appear to be interactive, not downloadable data.

Name: KITTITAS
notes: GIS includes datasets on water mitigation certificates and groundwater assessments; portal includes csv files on property sales, parcel values and building characteristics

Name: Ellensburg
notes: Website has an interactive Esri map gallery (http://gis.cityofellensburg.org/gallery/); also posts some budget information

Name: KLICKITAT
notes: Website ha interactive mapping function, but will only export to PDF/print/image

Name: Goldendale
notes: NA

Name: LEWIS
notes: includes half a dozen Shapefile; county website has other info (e.g., property sales) in PDF

Name: Centralia
notes: NA

Name: LINCOLN
notes: website says GIS is currently unavailable; website also includes a few PDFs of public health data

Name: Davenport
notes: NA

Name: MASON
notes: links take user to arcgis portal

Name: Shelton
notes: NA

Name: OKANOGAN
notes: NA

Name: Omak
notes: NA

Name: PACIFIC
notes: NA

Name: Raymond
notes: NA

Name: PEND OREILLE
notes: County has interactive maps on ArcGIS site (http://pendoreilleco.maps.arcgis.com/home/gallery.html?view=grid&sortOrder=asc&sortField=title) as well as some other open information thru PDF

Name: Newport
notes: no data on site, but homepage footer includes link to Northeast Washington Trends site

Name: PIERCE
notes: Googling Pierce Co open data gets several links, because Pierce also has interactive maps online (although with those it's easy to download the data!)

Name: Tacoma
notes: Tacoma pulls together open data and PDF documentation in a "Results253" site (https://data.cityoftacoma.org/)

Name: SAN JUAN
notes: County GIS site includes datasets about presence of fish species

Name: Friday Harbor
notes: Friday Harbor does post many PDFs of maps on its site

Name: SKAGIT
notes: Downloadable Assessor files include Sales. County website also has web-based interactive crime map (https://www.skagitcounty.net/Maps/iMap/?mapjs=crime)

Name: Mount Vernon
notes: no data on city site; search for "data" brings up links from 2012, some PDFs (but DEMS courses did show up!

Name: SKAMANIA
notes: assessor's office has GIS info for a fee, and provides historical data (e.g., sales) in PDF form

Name: Stevenson
notes: NA

Name: SNOHOMISH
notes: hard to navigate or understand; files provided mainly in Shapefile. You can easily find yourself on pages that look like someone's personal directory (ftp://ftp.snoco.org/Planning_and_Development_Services/GMA%20FUTURE%20LAND%20USE%20PLAN/SHAPEFILES/)

Name: Everett
notes: Everett's official city site has a "Data Center" aimed mainly at business/economic development; the pages capture demographics, etc. but in PDF form. Searching "data" on the city site will also bring up PDFs of older crime data, etc. (https://everettwa.gov/Search?searchPhrase=data)

Name: SPOKANE
notes: Has an "Open Data" page (https://www.spokanecounty.org/3948/Open-Data) but the actual open data boils down to GIS maps + Treasurer & Parcel zip files

Name: Spokane
notes: City website includes a lot more information on budget, elections, fire & crime, but in PDF form; also has interactive performance data (https://my.spokanecity.org/performs/); and interactive maps for crime (http://communitycrimemap.com/?address=Spokane,WA&zoom=11) and property

Name: STEVENS
notes: website has a long page describing GIS but doesn't appear to have any downloadable GIS data

Name: Colville
notes: has a link to Northeast Washington Trends on its "Links" page

Name: THURSTON
notes: NA

Name: Olympia
notes: provides a tiny bit of data in two or three PDFs on a "Plans, Studies & Data" page (http://olympiawa.gov/city-services/transportation-services/plans-studies-and-data.aspx)

Name: WAHKIAKUM
notes: county website does have a lot of PDF maps, as well as current minutes and agendae for government mtgs

Name: Cathlamet
notes: The 500+ person town has its town meeting minutes up to date on the website (https://www.townofcathlamet.com/blank)

Name: WALLA WALLA
notes: also provides interactive maps that require Adobe Flash; has long page of maps on many topics incl. animal control & irrigation, but these are all PDFs; downloadable data = Esri shapefiles

Name: Walla Walla
notes: GIS maps appear to be interactive web-based; additional data scattered around website but not available in downloadable sets

Name: WHATCOM
notes: County may have a few other xls files scattered around in the Document Center (https://www.whatcomcounty.us/documentcenter/)

Name: Bellingham
notes: city has other "Data" pages, which display visualizations of statistics, but don't appear to be downloadable; righthand menu from GIS page also has other info in PDF

Name: WHITMAN
notes: No, but they do mention GIS Weed mapping on the site

Name: Pullman
notes: the city has a News & Statistics page (http://www.pullman-wa.gov/departments/police/news-a-statistics) where you can get the latest incidents on the police blotter; it also has a Crime Mapping interactive site (Socrata)

Name: YAKIMA
notes: NA

Name: Yakima
notes: Traffic counts are provided in xls on a separate page (https://www.yakimawa.gov/services/streets/traffic-counts/); City does provide information in web-based interactive maps through its GIS portal (https://gis.yakimawa.gov/portal/home/)
